# Project principles

## Pace and scope

- Build step by step. Do not scaffold the full app in one pass unless explicitly asked.
- One focused change per task (e.g. theme tokens only, then one screen shell).
- After each step, summarize what changed and suggest the next step; wait for confirmation before starting the next feature unless asked to continue.
- Do not add npm packages without asking first.

## Audience

- Owner understands code but is not a full-time developer.
- Prefer clarity and small surface area over clever abstractions. Less is more.
- Name files and folders plainly; avoid deep nesting until it is needed.

## Design fidelity

- Consistency with the design system beats speed.
- The UI design is fixed; do not invent layout, copy, colors, spacing, or typography beyond provided specs and tokens.
- Do not add new visual details (colors, spacing, type scales) beyond what exists in `theme.css`.

## Component inventory

- Only use components listed in `docs/components.md`.
- Component list pending until finalized—do not create reusable components until the list is populated and approved.
- Do not add new reusable components without explicit approval.
- One-off layout markup inside a screen is fine; extracting a new shared component is not.

## Colors

- Use **palette tokens** from `theme.css` only (`--color-accent`, `--color-shade-*`, etc.) — no extra semantic color aliases beyond the palette.
- See `AGENTS.md` → **Colors (palette only)** for CSS, TS, PWA, and status bar rules.

## When blocked

- Missing token → stop; ask which palette color to use or request it be added to `src/styles/theme.css`.
- Missing asset → stop; ask for upload per `docs/assets.md` (no placeholders, icon packs, or generated substitutes).
- Missing copy → stop; ask for exact text or add it under `src/content/` first.

## When in doubt

- Ask questions instead of making assumptions.
- Consistency with the design system takes priority over speed.
